We identified 185 species, belonging to 62 families, as bioturbators on the UK shelf. Of those, only 14 species (8 %) were classed as burrowers, but those species had the highest bioturbation scores on average (Fig. 2
                     ). Vertical excavators made up 59 species (31 %) and had the second highest average bioturbation score (Fig. 2). Despite containing the highest number of species (64 species, 35 %), the sediment sifters had the lowest bioturbation scores on average (Fig. 2). The three species with the highest bioturbation score of 100 out of a maximum possible score of 125 were Myxine glutinosa (Atlantic Hagfish), Anguilla Anguilla (European eel), and Gadus morhua (Atlantic cod), while species with the lowest score of 3 were Nerophis lumbriciformis (Worm pipefish), Micrenophrys lilljeborgii (Norway bullhead), and Hippocampus hippocampus (Short snouted seahorse) (Fig. 3
                     ). The mean and median bioturbation scores across all species were 34 (±1.68) and 32 respectively.
